def: To cover over with, or as with, a mantle; to put about as aprotection. [Obs.] Holland.
Full of deeds or exploits; active; stirring. [R.] "A deedfullife." Tennyson.
Void of passion; without anger or emotion; not easily excited;calm. "Self-contained and passionless." Tennyson.
A pod dehiscent into two pieces or valves, and having the seedattached at one suture, as that of the pea.

Danger; risk; hazard; jeopardy; exposure of person or propertyto injury, loss, or destruction.In perils of waters, in perils of robbers. 2 Cor. xi. 26.Adventure hard With peril great achieved. Milton.At, or On, one's peril, with risk or danger to one; at the hazard of."On thy soul's peril." Shak.
A screed; a shred; a fragment. [R.]
Dark; gloomy; obscure; shaded; cheerless. [Poetic]He brought him through a darksome narrow pass To a broad gate, allbuilt of beaten gold. Spenser.
One of an extinct family of trees allied to the modern clubmosses, and including Lepidodendron and its allies.
The act of supposing; also, that which is supposed;supposition; opinion. Shak.Interest, with a Jew, never proceeds but upon supposal, at least, ofa firm and sufficient bottom. South.
To impress with terror; to coerce by intimidation.Humiliated by the tyranny of foreign despotism, and terrorized byecclesiastical authority. J. A. Symonds.
